    "34526750": {
      "title": "Percutaneous trocar (needle) nephrostomy in hydronephrosis",
      "abstract": "Willard Goodwin made many contributions to urology during a productive professional life, but it is a fair statement that his demonstration that percutaneous nephrostomy was possible and safe may have had the greatest lasting impact. As is often the case, when one reads the original article, one is struck by how simple it seems and wonders why it had not been done earlier. And then you realize that another 20 years elapsed after this article before percutaneous drainage became a common procedure, and then it was done not by urologists, but by radiologists. Goodwin used plain x-ray films to confirm placement of his trocars and tubes. Fluoroscopy was much less commonly available than today and, when available, it was securely in the hands of radiology. I do not know when Goodwin began to appreciate that it was fluoroscopy that would make this procedure practical, but it seems clear that it was the widespread availability of fluoroscopy that was the key to the popularity that percutaneous nephrostomy tube placement enjoys today. I believe that had there existed something like an \"endourology table\" in those days, we, and not radiology, would be putting these tubes in today, and we would have been doing it for 50 years and not just 25."
    }
